title.narrative: OUTPUT 1.5 EPI/MALARIA/HIV

description.narrative: Output 1.5: Government and partner institutions have the capacity and commitment to deliver quality services at scale to control vaccine preventable diseases, malaria and HIV, including elimination of neonatal tetanus, measles, HIV, syphilis and malaria, which contributes to Adolescent Health And Nutrition, Adolescents And Hiv/Aids, Child Health, Health Systems Strengthening, Hiv Prevention, Immunization, Immunization (Covid), Maternal And Newborn Health, Nutrition And Hiv, Polio Eradication, Protect, Care And Support Children And Families Affected By Hiv, Treatment And Care Of Children Living With Hiv. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Outcome 1: Women and children have more equitable access to evidence-based health, nutrition, Water, Sanitation, and Hygiene (WASH) and HIV services and adopt appropriate care practices from pregnancy to adolescence.

description.narrative: UNICEF supported closing the polio outbreak response in Papua and led key assessments including the expanded programme on immunization review and demand generation activities. UNICEF continues supporting malaria elimination efforts and is transitioning out of direct support in four provinces (Aceh, South Sulawesi, West Sulawesi, North Maluku) due to very successful achievements. UNICEF will concentrate its support in the highest burden provinces: Papua, Papua Barat, NTT, Maluku for the next five years. Extensive support has also been provided for ensuring continuity of malaria, HIV and immunization services during COVID-19 as well as preparation for the COVID-19 vaccine rollout. | Status:Met | As-of Date:03/12/2020
